<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[Gaurav]]></name></author>
<updated>2017-10-14T05:10:36-07:00</updated>
<published>2017-10-14T05:10:36-07:00</published>
<id>http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=8010&amp;p=34436#p34436</id>
<link href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=8010&amp;p=34436#p34436"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Win 10 desktop continually restarts, until CS 4.3.1 remo]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=8010&amp;p=34436#p34436"><![CDATA[
The way Windows 10 is serviced and updated, it routinely creates crashing issues for Explorer because Microsoft's upgrade process is imperfect even after years of trying and cannot even properly migrate desktop app settings after the upgrade - it ends up deleting certain configuration in the Registry. On a clean install of Windows 10's latest release, Classic Shell works. But often when in-place upgrades are done, Windows Setup damages it or causes serious issues due to their imperfect update process causing a partially installed state where Classic Shell crashes Explorer. I recommend you to stay with Windows 7 or 8.1 if you want to use Classic Shell.<br /><br />You could capture a crash dump as per these instructions: <!-- l --><a class="postlink-local" href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?f=12&amp;t=6">viewtopic.php?f=12&amp;t=6</a><!-- l --> but there are so many instability issues in general with Windows 10 that it is always going to give you problems. It's not a good, well-engineered system.<br /><br />Another thing you can try is download the Classic Shell Utility from here: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.mediafire.com/download/3ukeryzw41qpfz8/ClassicShellUtility.exe">http://www.mediafire.com/download/3uker ... tility.exe</a><!-- m --> and use it to clean all traces of Classic Shell from your existing installation, including all settings. Then try a clean install of the newest version.<br /><br />However we cannot guarantee it won't crash or break again because Microsoft designed Windows 10 to routinely break desktop apps that integrate deeply with the system.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=54">Gaurav</a> — Sat Oct 14, 2017 5:10 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
</entry>
<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[John Gray]]></name></author>
<updated>2017-10-14T03:48:55-07:00</updated>
<published>2017-10-14T03:48:55-07:00</published>
<id>http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=8010&amp;p=34435#p34435</id>
<link href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=8010&amp;p=34435#p34435"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Win 10 desktop continually restarts, until CS 4.3.1 removed]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=8010&amp;p=34435#p34435"><![CDATA[
Laptop is an HP EliteBook 8460p, which apparently does not support Windows 10, although it has been running Windows 10 quite happily for at least a year.<br /><br />I was asked to apply all the outstanding Windows Updates (about a year's worth!) to the Windows 10 Pro 64-bit operating system, so installed Classic Shell 4.3.1 (all options) and began.  <br /><br />After the latest and biggest update to version 1703, when the desktop came up it began continually wiping itself and redrawing all the desktop icons and the &quot;bottom line&quot; icons, in a continuous loop about 3-5 seconds in length.  It was almost impossible to do anything, apart from Ctrl-Alt-Del and Task Manager, where I was able with some difficulty to run TASKKILL CLASSICSTARTMENU.EXE, or to End Process on the same task in the list.  That 'solved' the problem of the continual desktop restart.<br /><br />I can't find any reference to this problem in the forum, so wonder what I can do to generate any diagnostic information.<br /><br />[As an aside, I had the same problem on a second 'identical' Elitebook 8460p, and reinstalled Windows 10 from a version 1703 ISO, then put on Classic Shell 4.3.1, and it works perfectly!]<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=25336">John Gray</a> — Sat Oct 14, 2017 3:48 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
